WEBVTT

00:06.006 --> 00:07.549
<i>[gentle music playing]</i>

00:15.390 --> 00:17.392
<i>By chance, I opened it.</i>

00:18.101 --> 00:22.063
<i>In my opinion, it's the most beautiful</i>
<i>of Nino Costa's poems.</i>

00:22.147 --> 00:24.315
<i>It's called </i>Rassa Nostrana.

00:26.109 --> 00:30.363
<i>"Most of the time a lost crop</i>
<i>or a fever or an accident at their job</i>

00:30.447 --> 00:35.076
<i>condemns them to a normal grave,</i>
<i>far away, in a foreign cemetery."</i>

00:35.827 --> 00:37.328
<i>What a beautiful ending.</i>

00:39.414 --> 00:43.001
<i>[man] The poem is dedicated to the people</i>
<i>of Piedmont who went to work abroad.</i>

00:43.084 --> 00:44.711
<i>Your father did the same, right?</i>

00:45.628 --> 00:47.255
<i>My dad moved to Argentina</i>

00:48.923 --> 00:52.260
<i>when he was 22 or 23.</i>
<i>I don't remember exactly.</i>

00:52.343 --> 00:55.305
<i>He used to work at the Bank of Italy.</i>
<i>He was an accountant.</i>

00:57.140 --> 00:59.809
<i>[man] At a certain point, you felt</i>
<i>the call to priesthood, right?</i>

01:01.061 --> 01:02.937
<i>Before that,</i>
<i>what job did you have in mind?</i>

01:03.021 --> 01:04.439
<i>Yeah, I was into chemistry.</i>

01:04.522 --> 01:06.524
<i>["Dali's Salvation</i>
<i>(Everything Everywhere)" playing]</i>

01:06.608 --> 01:11.613
<i>♪ If I wanna doo-doo</i>
<i>Doo-doo-dn-doo-doo, I will ♪</i>

01:11.696 --> 01:15.450
<i>♪ I shall, I can ♪</i>

01:15.533 --> 01:19.079
<i>♪ You see a face</i>
<i>But I see butterfly wings ♪</i>

01:19.162 --> 01:23.166
<i>♪ A song is time that sings ♪</i>

01:23.249 --> 01:26.628
<i>♪ I want a place in the sun</i>
<i>That shines in the rain ♪</i>

01:26.711 --> 01:31.716
<i>♪ A song is time explained ♪</i>

01:31.800 --> 01:36.971
<i>♪ I can get everything everywhere ♪</i>

01:37.055 --> 01:42.352
<i>♪ I can get everything everywhere ♪</i>

01:48.358 --> 01:50.318
<i>May I tell you a personal anecdote?</i>

01:51.111 --> 01:56.574
<i>When I finished elementary school</i>
<i>at 12 years old, my father told me,</i>

01:56.658 --> 02:00.495
<i>"You will have one month of vacation</i>
<i>to spend with your grandparents."</i>

02:01.788 --> 02:04.958
<i>"But the other two months</i>
<i>you are going to work."</i>

02:06.793 --> 02:10.505
<i>And he sent me</i>
<i>to the hosiery factory of a friend.</i>

02:12.090 --> 02:14.300
<i>And he didn't send me to work at the desk,</i>

02:15.009 --> 02:15.927
<i>but to clean.</i>

02:17.428 --> 02:21.641
<i>So I experienced work</i>
<i>as a source of dignity,</i>

02:22.142 --> 02:24.018
<i>without realizing it gave me dignity.</i>

02:25.937 --> 02:27.438
<i>[gentle music playing]</i>

02:34.487 --> 02:39.284
<i>[woman] </i>My full name is
Oyenike Monica Davies-Okundaye.

02:41.494 --> 02:43.288
<i>I'm 70 years old.</i>

02:44.455 --> 02:47.000
<i>I'm an artist known over the world.</i>

02:48.042 --> 02:54.632
<i>Each one of my dresses is made by me,</i>
<i>because I have to wear what I made.</i>

02:59.304 --> 03:02.265
<i>I come to Lagos to do several exhibitions,</i>

03:02.348 --> 03:05.059
<i>which I don't even know,</i>
<i>it's more than 100.</i>

03:05.143 --> 03:07.103
<i>Wow.</i>

03:07.896 --> 03:10.440
<i>That is how my work gets recognized.</i>

03:12.108 --> 03:13.902
<i>I have gone through hell,</i>

03:13.985 --> 03:19.073
<i>and I was able to come out</i>
<i>because my work is what gives me…</i>

03:21.242 --> 03:22.243
<i>independence.</i>

03:23.077 --> 03:24.621
<i>[uplifting music playing]</i>

03:29.959 --> 03:32.337
<i>[Nike] </i>I always go home every year.

03:32.921 --> 03:36.966
<i>It's good for the eye.</i>
<i>It's also good for the memory.</i>

03:38.593 --> 03:42.555
<i>Almost 50-something years ago,</i>

03:42.639 --> 03:45.475
<i>compared to now, Nigeria has changed!</i>

03:46.434 --> 03:50.355
<i>In those days, especially women,</i>

03:51.231 --> 03:54.400
<i>they don't travel much like men,</i>
<i>they only go to farm.</i>

03:54.484 --> 03:55.443
<i>[chuckles]</i>

03:59.072 --> 04:03.076
<i>I must come back and pay my homage</i>
<i>to the goddess of the river.</i>

04:04.410 --> 04:09.874
<i>To thank Osun for what she has done for</i>
<i>me in the past and to ask for a new favor.</i>

04:14.504 --> 04:16.005
<i>[pensive music playing]</i>

04:20.635 --> 04:22.387
<i>[woman] </i>We were born with a gift.

04:24.639 --> 04:25.765
<i>No one taught us.</i>

04:28.810 --> 04:31.646
<i>Before anything happened,</i>
<i>I dreamt about how I'd do it.</i>

04:37.986 --> 04:41.614
<i>In the dream, there was a pregnant woman.</i>

04:43.866 --> 04:45.994
<i>I was afraid. "How am I going to do this?"</i>

04:47.912 --> 04:48.955
<i>A tall woman.</i>

04:50.999 --> 04:54.168
<i>The pregnant lady lies down,</i>
<i>and the woman tells me,</i>

04:54.794 --> 04:56.379
<i>"This is how, Natalia."</i>

04:58.131 --> 04:59.090
<i>And I got to work.</i>

05:04.470 --> 05:07.307
<i>My name is Natalia Echeverría Fuentevilla.</i>

05:08.933 --> 05:10.476
<i>I'm 72 years old.</i>

05:12.353 --> 05:13.354
<i>I'm a midwife.</i>

05:14.981 --> 05:16.983
<i>I can't remember</i>
<i>how many deliveries I've done.</i>

05:17.734 --> 05:20.236
<i>More than 3,000, but I don't keep count.</i>

05:20.320 --> 05:22.322
<i>[heart beating slowly]</i>

05:25.074 --> 05:26.534
<i>[heart beating rapidly]</i>

05:31.581 --> 05:34.500
<i>-[Natalia] Is it moving?</i>
<i>-[woman] Yes, it's moving.</i>

05:44.385 --> 05:47.847
<i>Sometimes, when it's like this,</i>
<i>we don't know what it is,</i>

05:49.307 --> 05:51.726
<i>but we always know that</i>
<i>when it's on the right side,</i>

05:53.269 --> 05:54.103
<i>that it's a boy.</i>

05:57.357 --> 06:00.777
<i>Sara is already strong. She looks healthy.</i>

06:01.986 --> 06:03.321
<i>Her feet aren't swollen.</i>

06:04.530 --> 06:05.656
<i>Her heartbeat is fine.</i>

06:08.951 --> 06:12.080
<i>I'll visit twice a day</i>
<i>to see how she's doing.</i>

06:15.375 --> 06:17.960
<i>Every day she's getting ready</i>
<i>for the baby,</i>

06:19.462 --> 06:21.005
<i>and now she's a few days away.</i>

06:24.801 --> 06:27.512
<i>[Pope Francis] It came to mind,</i>
<i>and I'll say this with gratitude,</i>

06:28.304 --> 06:32.767
<i>the midwife who delivered me</i>
<i>and my five siblings, all of them, all.</i>

06:33.768 --> 06:37.647
<i>At home, we used to keep the basin,</i>
<i>shaped like a bedpan,</i>

06:38.439 --> 06:40.233
<i>that she used to deliver us.</i>

06:41.943 --> 06:45.738
<i>And if the baby was fine,</i>
<i>she'd cut the cord, care for the mother,</i>

06:45.822 --> 06:48.658
<i>and let the baby cry.</i>
<i>[chuckling] She'd leave him there.</i>

06:49.283 --> 06:51.494
<i>I remember that woman, who…</i>

06:53.871 --> 06:55.498
<i>when I was 17 years old,</i>

06:56.082 --> 06:58.918
<i>she celebrated her 5,000th delivery.</i>

07:02.004 --> 07:06.592
<i>And I remember, when I was a child,</i>
<i>she'd come with her tiny suitcase,</i>

07:06.676 --> 07:09.220
<i>and I'd tell my brother,</i>
<i>"Palanconi is here!"</i>

07:09.303 --> 07:11.055
<i>Her name was María Luisa Palanconi.</i>

07:11.139 --> 07:13.349
<i>"Palanconi is here.</i>
<i>We're going to have a new brother."</i>

07:14.100 --> 07:17.812
<i>This woman, who was the first</i>
<i>to hold me in her hands,</i>

07:19.105 --> 07:22.733
<i>she gives life,</i>
<i>receives life, respects life.</i>

07:22.817 --> 07:26.362
<i>There is something sacred about a midwife.</i>

07:28.990 --> 07:30.533
<i>[man] Is it possible, at work,</i>

07:30.616 --> 07:33.828
<i>to combine fantasy,</i>
<i>perspective and tenacity?</i>

07:35.997 --> 07:39.959
<i>If you want your work to be fruitful,</i>
<i>you have to combine those things,</i>

07:40.042 --> 07:41.085
<i>otherwise, it won't be.</i>

07:42.211 --> 07:45.923
<i>And, somehow…</i>
<i>I was going to say, balance them, no…</i>

07:46.007 --> 07:47.258
<i>harmonize them.</i>

07:47.758 --> 07:49.093
<i>[gentle music playing]</i>

07:54.891 --> 07:56.893
<i>-[machines whirring]</i>
<i>-[traffic buzzing]</i>

07:56.976 --> 07:58.019
<i>[machines squeaking]</i>

07:59.687 --> 08:02.648
<i>[man] </i>Today, my health is very important…

08:06.235 --> 08:08.821
<i>because my job is taxing.</i>

08:13.910 --> 08:14.744
<i>Goodbye.</i>

08:16.704 --> 08:18.122
<i>I'm Trinh Ngoc.</i>

08:19.916 --> 08:22.084
<i>I'm a talented Vietnamese shoemaker.</i>

08:22.168 --> 08:23.586
<i>NGOC SHOES</i>

08:23.669 --> 08:26.214
<i>I think every man needs to work,</i>

08:27.715 --> 08:30.676
<i>work like ants, like bees.</i>

08:33.930 --> 08:35.890
<i>They work all their lives.</i>

08:38.851 --> 08:42.104
<i>My beautiful profession</i>
<i>requires five elements.</i>

08:44.398 --> 08:47.527
<i>The first is passion, the heart.</i>

08:49.946 --> 08:52.823
<i>Second is creativity, the brain.</i>

08:54.909 --> 08:57.453
<i>Third is the eyes, for observation.</i>

08:58.788 --> 09:00.498
<i>The fourth is the hands.</i>

09:02.458 --> 09:05.378
<i>And the fifth is the will.</i>

09:06.671 --> 09:08.297
<i>Five. Five elements.</i>

09:14.554 --> 09:17.056
<i>In the 1950s, I went to Cambodia…</i>

09:17.139 --> 09:18.724
<i>GLORIOUS CAMBODIA</i>
<i>HAIR SALON</i>

09:20.059 --> 09:22.562
<i>…to open a shop</i>
<i>in the center of Phnom Penh.</i>

09:27.400 --> 09:29.735
<i>We had European customers.</i>

09:29.819 --> 09:35.908
<i>French, American,</i>
<i>English, and even Russians.</i>

09:41.497 --> 09:44.250
<i>I worked during the day and evenings.</i>

09:46.627 --> 09:50.047
<i>Month after month,</i>
<i>I achieved good success.</i>

09:53.718 --> 09:59.473
<i>The king, one day, sent a car</i>
<i>that stopped in front of my shop</i>

10:01.517 --> 10:02.560
<i>to order shoes.</i>

10:08.065 --> 10:08.899
<i>Here it is.</i>

10:10.151 --> 10:12.320
<i>This is modeled after the king's foot.</i>

10:15.656 --> 10:17.158
<i>King Norodom Sihanouk.</i>

10:21.495 --> 10:22.872
<i>In 1970,</i>

10:24.874 --> 10:25.750
<i>was…</i>

10:28.711 --> 10:29.545
<i>was the coup.</i>

10:36.177 --> 10:38.846
<i>Many Vietnamese people were slaughtered.</i>

10:40.723 --> 10:43.851
<i>They made 29 arrests, but me…</i>

10:43.934 --> 10:47.730
<i>I'm, out of 29, the only survivor.</i>
<i>The only one.</i>

10:51.442 --> 10:53.527
<i>And everything changed. Everything.</i>

11:04.246 --> 11:08.250
<i>[Nike] </i>My village is a small village
surrounded with mountains.

11:09.627 --> 11:11.337
<i>I was born into poverty.</i>

11:11.879 --> 11:15.216
<i>Hardly I ate more than once in a day.</i>

11:15.299 --> 11:16.717
<i>[children chattering]</i>

11:16.801 --> 11:19.220
<i>[Nike] </i>My mother died
when I was six years old.

11:19.887 --> 11:23.140
<i>My great-grandmother, that raised me,</i>

11:23.224 --> 11:28.270
<i>put a thread on the calabash for me</i>
<i>to start teaching me how to weave</i>

11:28.771 --> 11:30.773
<i>at the age of eight years old.</i>

11:32.233 --> 11:35.319
<i>She teached me</i>
<i>how to remove seed from the cotton,</i>

11:35.403 --> 11:39.615
<i>how to spindle it, how to turn it</i>
<i>into cotton before we put it on the loom.</i>

11:39.699 --> 11:41.701
<i>[inspirational music crescendos]</i>

11:49.083 --> 11:53.045
<i>[chanting in Yoruba]</i>
<i>♪ </i>Nike our valuable and esteemed one ♪

11:53.129 --> 11:55.131
<i>♪ Highly respected woman of honor… ♪</i>

11:56.507 --> 11:59.093
<i>[Nike] </i>I was 13, going to 14.

12:00.136 --> 12:02.221
<i>My father needed some money.</i>

12:03.848 --> 12:07.935
<i>He now wanted to marry me off</i>
<i>to a junior minister.</i>

12:09.603 --> 12:11.397
<i>[chanting continues in background]</i>

12:13.441 --> 12:16.235
<i>[Nike] </i>You know, sometimes,
we are born to submit.

12:17.361 --> 12:20.322
<i>We are not even allowed</i>
<i>to look at your parents' eyes</i>

12:20.406 --> 12:21.949
<i>when they're talking to you.</i>

12:25.786 --> 12:27.163
<i>The minister looked at me.</i>

12:27.246 --> 12:30.666
<i>He said, "In another two or three years</i>
<i>you will be in love."</i>

12:32.334 --> 12:34.211
<i>I told him, "I want to go pee."</i>

12:35.629 --> 12:39.884
<i>In our place, you don't have toilets,</i>
<i>so you just pee outside in the bush.</i>

12:41.927 --> 12:43.637
<i>That is how I ran away.</i>

12:48.601 --> 12:50.394
<i>Freedom is everything.</i>

12:51.771 --> 12:54.482
<i>I'm taking the biggest risk of my life.</i>

12:54.565 --> 12:56.317
<i>[uplifting music playing]</i>

12:56.400 --> 12:59.862
<i>I know I can work</i>
<i>and I know I can make it in life.</i>

13:01.363 --> 13:02.531
<i>[music continues]</i>

13:19.131 --> 13:21.383
<i>[Francesca] What did you want to do</i>
<i>when you were a kid?</i>

13:21.467 --> 13:23.135
<i>We come from a tough place.</i>

13:23.636 --> 13:25.638
<i>But it was a real… Like, a village.</i>

13:26.222 --> 13:30.643
<i>Three butcher shops in the same street,</i>
<i>funeral parlors everywhere, flower shops,</i>

13:30.726 --> 13:34.980
<i>pasticcerias</i>, where the<i> </i>incredible
Italian pastries were made.

13:35.064 --> 13:36.649
<i>It was just wonderful in that way.</i>

13:36.732 --> 13:38.067
<i>ITALIAN BOOKSTORE</i>

13:38.150 --> 13:39.693
<i>[gypsy jazz music playing]</i>

13:43.489 --> 13:44.615
<i>[Martin] </i>But it was scary.

13:45.115 --> 13:49.036
<i>You're in the streets</i>
<i>and literally on the Bowery, uh,</i>

13:49.119 --> 13:51.914
<i>with the homeless people,</i>
<i>the… the alcoholics,</i>

13:51.997 --> 13:54.917
<i>kids running in the streets,</i>
<i>playing, fighting.</i>

13:55.000 --> 13:56.961
<i>I had to be very careful</i>
<i>because the tough guys</i>

13:57.044 --> 13:58.462
<i>were really tough, the kids.</i>

14:00.297 --> 14:02.591
<i>Along with all that, I was always sick.</i>

14:03.634 --> 14:05.678
<i>Some of my fondest memories, oddly enough,</i>

14:05.761 --> 14:11.141
<i>are of my father getting</i>
<i>my asthma medication, allergy shots.</i>

14:11.225 --> 14:13.644
<i>My mother helping me breathe</i>
<i>when I had asthma attacks.</i>

14:14.979 --> 14:17.940
<i>I couldn't join any of the other sports</i>
<i>or anything like that.</i>

14:19.191 --> 14:23.195
<i>So, the movie theater</i>
<i>became something like a… a refuge.</i>

14:23.279 --> 14:25.072
<i>[solemn music playing]</i>

14:32.997 --> 14:36.208
<i>[Martin] </i>The other place that was
fairly safe was the church.

14:39.253 --> 14:41.171
<i>The church had contemplation.</i>

14:41.255 --> 14:44.383
<i>The church had a kind of meditative state.</i>

14:48.721 --> 14:54.184
<i>I started thinking that the priesthood</i>
<i>would be a fast lane for saving my soul.</i>

14:55.144 --> 14:56.437
<i>[chuckles] Really?</i>

14:56.520 --> 14:57.354
<i>You know.</i>

15:04.820 --> 15:06.363
<i>[Trinh] </i>This one's a classic.

15:08.282 --> 15:10.284
<i>It's been around for generations.</i>

15:12.661 --> 15:14.997
<i>-Is that from the '30s, '40s?</i>
<i>-That's correct.</i>

15:15.497 --> 15:16.415
<i>Can I order this model?</i>

15:16.498 --> 15:17.708
<i>-You like this one?</i>
<i>-Yes.</i>

15:21.086 --> 15:23.130
<i>TOE MORE OFF-WHITE</i>

15:24.340 --> 15:28.135
<i>[Trinh] </i>In 1970,
there was a coup in Cambodia.

15:29.428 --> 15:30.554
<i>The night it happened,</i>

15:30.638 --> 15:36.560
<i>I remember some Cambodian soldiers</i>
<i>knocking on the door of my shop.</i>

15:39.396 --> 15:41.732
<i>They kept knocking for five minutes.</i>

15:41.815 --> 15:45.569
<i>And that night,</i>
<i>they arrested many of my friends.</i>

15:46.654 --> 15:48.697
<i>And after that, they all died.</i>

15:49.782 --> 15:50.866
<i>They all died.</i>

16:02.670 --> 16:06.256
<i>And that's why</i>
<i>I had to go back to Vietnam.</i>

16:13.138 --> 16:17.685
<i>It was really hard on me</i>
<i>because I left everything in Cambodia.</i>

16:19.853 --> 16:24.108
<i>The leather, the materials,</i>
<i>the customers, the machines.</i>

16:26.068 --> 16:29.196
<i>I thought my time making shoes was over.</i>

16:33.742 --> 16:35.202
<i>But deep down in my heart…</i>

16:38.288 --> 16:39.164
<i>Shoes.</i>

16:40.040 --> 16:41.000
<i>Shoes.</i>

16:41.083 --> 16:43.085
<i>[inspirational music playing]</i>

16:55.639 --> 16:57.057
<i>Facing the post-war period…</i>

16:59.476 --> 17:02.896
<i>I remember what Dona Concetta told me.</i>

17:04.857 --> 17:06.817
<i>She was a Sicilian lady who…</i>

17:07.609 --> 17:11.363
<i>whose job was helping…</i>
<i>my mother wash her clothes.</i>

17:13.615 --> 17:17.661
<i>This woman, who didn't know how to write,</i>

17:20.372 --> 17:24.168
<i>had to give birth to her second son</i>

17:24.251 --> 17:26.295
<i>while her husband was away at war.</i>

17:26.795 --> 17:30.090
<i>She had to walk</i>
<i>along the railroad to the hospital,</i>

17:31.592 --> 17:32.426
<i>kilometers away.</i>

17:36.013 --> 17:37.473
<i>The failure of being at war.</i>

17:38.140 --> 17:39.725
<i>The failure of being a widow.</i>

17:40.392 --> 17:41.769
<i>Two children with her.</i>

17:43.312 --> 17:46.732
<i>She took the first ship</i>
<i>to America to start again.</i>

17:49.234 --> 17:52.905
<i>She was 91 years old when I saw her die.</i>

17:52.988 --> 17:55.032
<i>I was the Archbishop of Buenos Aires.</i>

17:56.450 --> 17:58.160
<i>She'd known me since I was little.</i>

17:59.995 --> 18:03.457
<i>Let this memory be a tribute</i>
<i>to the many men and women</i>

18:04.208 --> 18:05.876
<i>who didn't stay down,</i>

18:06.585 --> 18:09.880
<i>but asked for help,</i>
<i>and got up again after failure,</i>

18:09.963 --> 18:11.381
<i>and kept going.</i>

18:13.008 --> 18:14.551
<i>And she never lost her joy.</i>

18:15.803 --> 18:17.596
<i>[uplifting music playing]</i>

18:21.475 --> 18:25.729
<i>[Nike] </i>I remember
I left, uh, 5th of May, 1966.

18:26.688 --> 18:30.400
<i>I was afraid because I don't know</i>
<i>what could happen to me.</i>

18:31.193 --> 18:33.362
<i>Either I make it or die.</i>

18:34.613 --> 18:35.781
<i>[music continues]</i>

18:38.200 --> 18:40.786
<i>[Nike] </i>I came to Osogbo in July.

18:42.454 --> 18:45.249
<i>I opened my first gallery in my bedroom.</i>

18:45.332 --> 18:47.334
<i>I put the clothes on the floor.</i>

18:49.002 --> 18:51.672
<i>I was selling my art at the Bar Beach,</i>

18:52.798 --> 18:57.845
<i>one dollar, one naira,</i>
<i>one shilling, two shillings…</i>

18:58.846 --> 19:01.265
<i>And that is how I was able to survive.</i>

19:07.604 --> 19:09.940
<i>My first husband is an artist.</i>

19:11.150 --> 19:13.277
<i>We have 14 other wives.</i>

19:16.864 --> 19:18.824
<i>We are three wives living in one room.</i>

19:19.867 --> 19:21.243
<i>It's very difficult</i>

19:21.326 --> 19:23.537
<i>because if the husband is</i>
<i>with somebody here,</i>

19:24.163 --> 19:27.416
<i>you have to just pretend</i>
<i>you are sleeping! [laughs]</i>

19:28.250 --> 19:31.879
<i>You have to pretend you are sleeping,</i>
<i>so you don't know what is going on.</i>

19:31.962 --> 19:35.007
<i>Because sometimes,</i>
<i>when you talk at him… [clears throat]</i>

19:35.090 --> 19:37.301
<i>…he will say,</i>
<i>"Ah, you are jealous!" [laughs]</i>

19:42.014 --> 19:43.640
<i>The first time was very bitter.</i>

19:44.349 --> 19:47.603
<i>But later on,</i>
<i>I decided to teach them the </i>adire<i>.</i>

19:47.686 --> 19:49.646
<i>So, that is how we become friends.</i>

19:53.275 --> 19:57.154
<i>Adire</i>, that is the name of the textile.

19:57.237 --> 19:59.031
<i>We do it and we dye it.</i>

19:59.573 --> 20:00.657
<i>It's what </i>adire<i> means.</i>

20:02.784 --> 20:05.204
<i>We have to mold the indigo into a ball.</i>

20:05.287 --> 20:09.249
<i>They put it inside the bowl,</i>
<i>it will stay for seven good days</i>

20:09.333 --> 20:11.001
<i>before it becomes fermented.</i>

20:11.585 --> 20:14.755
<i>-Every day, you have to be stirring it.</i>

20:14.838 --> 20:15.881
<i>[in Yoruba] Keep stirring.</i>

20:16.840 --> 20:19.676
<i>[in English] Every day,</i>
<i>you have to stir it for three hours.</i>

20:19.760 --> 20:23.972
<i>This one is going to take three days</i>
<i>of dyeing before it's ready.</i>

20:25.515 --> 20:27.601
<i>We're going to leave it inside the dye…</i>

20:30.854 --> 20:33.148
<i>for it to go very dark.</i>

20:36.443 --> 20:38.362
<i>I love training people.</i>

20:39.154 --> 20:41.531
<i>It is just like you are sowing a seed…</i>

20:44.243 --> 20:46.828
<i>and that seed will grow.</i>

20:49.957 --> 20:51.959
<i>You studied to become a priest.</i>

20:52.459 --> 20:55.379
<i>What made you change</i>
<i>your mind and your path?</i>

20:55.879 --> 20:59.258
<i>What happened with that was,</i>
<i>there was this young priest who came in</i>

20:59.341 --> 21:02.094
<i>and became part of the parish,</i>
<i>Father Francis Principe.</i>

21:02.177 --> 21:03.512
<i>[gentle music playing]</i>

21:06.431 --> 21:08.850
<i>[Martin] </i>He started giving us books
written by Graham Green,

21:09.351 --> 21:11.520
<i>The Power and The Glory,</i>
<i>The End of the Affair.</i>

21:12.145 --> 21:15.649
<i>James Joyce</i>, A Portrait of the Artist
as a Young Man, The Dubliners,

21:16.149 --> 21:17.317
<i>all of these things.</i>

21:18.485 --> 21:19.903
<i>I also brought books into the house,</i>

21:19.987 --> 21:23.740
<i>one on the Russian Revolution by</i>
<i>Alan Moorehead and the other on Greek art.</i>

21:26.118 --> 21:28.537
<i>Yeah, 'cause I was</i>
<i>fascinated by the ancient world.</i>

21:28.620 --> 21:31.456
<i>My parents looked at me strangely.</i>

21:33.542 --> 21:35.794
<i>But they were</i>
<i>very concerned about all that.</i>

21:35.877 --> 21:36.878
<i>[Martin] Well?</i>

21:38.046 --> 21:41.383
<i>Is that all for today? Now, listen,</i>
<i>could I put my furniture back?</i>

21:41.466 --> 21:43.093
<i>-[Martin] What furniture?</i>
<i>-Things in here.</i>

21:43.176 --> 21:45.387
<i>-Is he still taking this?</i>
<i>-[Martin] No. [laughs]</i>

21:45.470 --> 21:48.056
<i>Oh, Marty, you won't get out</i>
<i>of this house alive!</i>

21:51.977 --> 21:53.770
<i>[Martin] </i>Father Principe became a mentor.

21:55.272 --> 21:56.648
<i>He would look at us and say,</i>

21:56.732 --> 21:58.859
<i>"You don't have to do it</i>
<i>the way your parents did."</i>

21:59.443 --> 22:01.653
<i>"It doesn't work that way now.</i>
<i>The world is different."</i>

22:01.737 --> 22:03.322
<i>"Experience."</i>

22:03.405 --> 22:04.281
<i>"Learn."</i>

22:05.282 --> 22:06.491
<i>And it made sense.</i>

22:07.034 --> 22:08.452
<i>It really made sense.</i>

22:08.535 --> 22:10.704
<i>[Academy Awards theme music playing]</i>

22:14.958 --> 22:18.128
<i>[Martin] </i>First time
that the Academy Awards were televised,

22:18.795 --> 22:20.547
<i>we just loved watching it.</i>

22:22.591 --> 22:24.343
<i>Father Principe came in</i>
<i>to talk to the kids,</i>

22:25.552 --> 22:27.304
<i>"I want you to remember one thing."</i>

22:27.387 --> 22:29.431
<i>He said,</i>
<i>"Do you see the idol behind them?"</i>

22:30.015 --> 22:31.558
<i>"That's Moloch."</i>

22:31.641 --> 22:33.477
<i>"That's a graven image."</i>

22:33.977 --> 22:36.355
<i>And we said,</i>
<i>"Oh, he's spoiling all the fun." [laughs]</i>

22:37.564 --> 22:40.400
<i>But then he said,</i>
<i>"No, what I mean is don't go for that."</i>

22:40.484 --> 22:42.152
<i>"Don't let that…</i>
<i>Don't let that take over."</i>

22:42.235 --> 22:44.780
<i>Don't go for the wrong value,</i>
<i>he's talking about,</i>

22:44.863 --> 22:49.493
<i>'cause creativity</i>
<i>is a… a grace and a… and a blessing,</i>

22:49.576 --> 22:51.828
<i>and it's a responsibility.</i>

22:52.621 --> 22:54.998
<i>And keep that… keep that protected.</i>

22:55.082 --> 22:57.000
<i>The work itself is the reward.</i>

22:59.961 --> 23:04.424
<i>And so the passion and the obsession</i>
<i>that I felt with the vocation,</i>

23:04.508 --> 23:08.512
<i>for the wrong reasons,</i>
<i>was placed into the creativity.</i>

23:09.179 --> 23:11.515
<i>So, I didn't make it as a priest.</i>

23:17.229 --> 23:18.313
<i>[Pope Francis] Creativity.</i>

23:19.398 --> 23:21.274
<i>There's a Greek word</i>
<i>that describes it well.</i>

23:22.192 --> 23:23.151
<i>Poetry, right?</i>

23:23.944 --> 23:25.529
<i>Creativity is poetry.</i>

23:25.612 --> 23:28.448
<i>We believe that a poet just daydreams</i>
<i>and says things.</i>

23:30.158 --> 23:31.827
<i>A creator is a poet.</i>

23:33.036 --> 23:35.497
<i>When you create anything, you are a poet.</i>

23:36.081 --> 23:37.666
<i>I mean, you make poetry.</i>

23:39.376 --> 23:41.837
<i>There's no dignity without creativity.</i>

23:41.920 --> 23:43.839
<i>Dignity leads to creation.</i>

23:43.922 --> 23:47.509
<i>Because there is no selfishness</i>
<i>in giving life to something.</i>

23:51.138 --> 23:54.307
<i>One always works for the other,</i>

23:56.476 --> 23:58.895
<i>the company, the world, the family.</i>

23:59.646 --> 24:01.898
<i>But there's always otherness in work.</i>

24:01.982 --> 24:03.692
<i>-</i>[crowd cheering]
-Hallelujah!

24:08.572 --> 24:10.073
<i>[man] </i>I'm Moshe Basson,

24:11.241 --> 24:14.411
<i>chef of The Eucalyptus</i>
<i>restaurant in Jerusalem.</i>

24:15.787 --> 24:19.291
<i>I'm 70 and making biblical food.</i>

24:21.376 --> 24:23.003
<i>This is what we're doing, really.</i>

24:24.004 --> 24:28.133
<i>The food that was served</i>
<i>in the time of Jesus.</i>

24:33.805 --> 24:40.353
<i>We are making risotto from </i>freekeh<i>,</i>
<i>or </i>carmel <i>as it's mentioned in the Bible.</i>

24:41.354 --> 24:46.109
<i>And this is the food that young David</i>
<i>carried to the battlefield</i>

24:46.193 --> 24:49.821
<i>as a takeaway for his brothers,</i>
<i>and then he's killing Goliath.</i>

24:49.905 --> 24:52.616
<i>[in Hebrew] The horseradish is strong.</i>
<i>It's spicy, yes?</i>

24:55.285 --> 24:59.206
<i>I believe in each</i>
<i>of these stories that it's true.</i>

25:03.001 --> 25:07.464
<i>I love the tradition</i>
<i>because it's involving everything.</i>

25:08.840 --> 25:14.304
<i>I'm named after Moses because</i>
<i>my grandfather was Moses, Moshe.</i>

25:14.387 --> 25:17.849
<i>His grandfather was Moshe,</i>
<i>and his grandfather was Moshe.</i>

25:17.933 --> 25:22.145
<i>Every first-born in the family</i>
<i>for generations was Moshe.</i>

25:29.194 --> 25:30.695
<i>I was born in Iraq.</i>

25:31.655 --> 25:36.826
<i>Till June '41, Jewish in Iraq</i>
<i>were very safe and free.</i>

25:38.286 --> 25:41.998
<i>June '41 was the first-ever pogrom</i>
<i>in the Jewish of Iraq,</i>

25:42.082 --> 25:45.043
<i>arranged by the Nazi ambassador</i>

25:45.752 --> 25:48.588
<i>to Baghdad and the </i>Mufti<i> of Jerusalem,</i>

25:48.672 --> 25:52.968
<i>a friend of Hitler that went there</i>
<i>to urge them to attack the Jewish.</i>

25:53.051 --> 25:54.302
<i>[tense music playing]</i>

25:55.178 --> 25:57.514
<i>-[music stops]</i>
<i>-[man praying over PA]</i>

26:02.227 --> 26:07.399
<i>[Moshe] </i>In this pogrom a lot of people
were hanged, killed, raped.

26:11.570 --> 26:14.614
<i>That's what made my parents decide</i>

26:15.115 --> 26:18.910
<i>to leave the good life in Iraq</i>

26:18.994 --> 26:22.581
<i>and to move to this unknown destination.</i>

26:25.333 --> 26:29.713
<i>So, I arrived in Jerusalem</i>
<i>when I was, like, nine months.</i>

26:31.590 --> 26:33.300
<i>I was a baby refugee.</i>

26:35.260 --> 26:37.429
<i>Natural lemonade. It's cold.</i>

26:38.388 --> 26:40.724
<i>Natural lemonade. Lemonade, anyone.</i>

26:41.975 --> 26:43.727
<i>Natural lemonade.</i>

26:43.810 --> 26:45.812
<i>[peddler speaking Spanish over PA]</i>

26:53.653 --> 26:56.823
<i>[Natalia] </i>My children aren't here.
They live far away.

26:58.783 --> 26:59.951
<i>They left years ago.</i>

27:02.621 --> 27:05.665
<i>The sea is drying up, so there's no work.</i>

27:07.292 --> 27:09.461
<i>WELCOME TO SAN MATEO DEL MAR</i>

27:10.545 --> 27:12.380
<i>That's why no one has money anymore.</i>

27:13.965 --> 27:16.593
<i>Well, there were fishermen.</i>
<i>There used to be the sea.</i>

27:17.719 --> 27:20.597
<i>There used to be lots of fish and shrimp,</i>

27:21.306 --> 27:24.059
<i>but now, it's disappearing.</i>

27:25.644 --> 27:28.813
<i>And without water, we can't stay here.</i>

27:29.314 --> 27:30.315
<i>How can we live?</i>

27:34.444 --> 27:36.529
<i>Here, the midwives don't have any gauze</i>

27:38.323 --> 27:40.700
<i>or scissors to cut the umbilical cord.</i>

27:43.578 --> 27:46.665
<i>Sara, I think that she is doing very well.</i>

27:48.500 --> 27:49.959
<i>Her face looks very good.</i>

27:52.504 --> 27:53.713
<i>The water's broken.</i>

27:54.881 --> 27:55.924
<i>It'll be time soon.</i>

27:58.885 --> 28:01.429
<i>That movement is the baby</i>
<i>getting ready to be born.</i>

28:06.017 --> 28:07.852
<i>It won't take more than 24 hours.</i>

28:22.909 --> 28:24.369
<i>Okay, I'm finished.</i>

28:24.452 --> 28:26.287
<i>Leave the rest in the fridge for me.</i>

28:26.996 --> 28:28.123
<i>I'm full for now.</i>

28:28.998 --> 28:31.584
<i>-You're heading upstairs?</i>
<i>-I'll go up and change.</i>

28:37.924 --> 28:40.301
<i>Here in Saigon, I tried to survive.</i>

28:41.970 --> 28:43.888
<i>I went back to designing,</i>

28:45.682 --> 28:51.104
<i>making drawings and decorations</i>
<i>for high-end shops and exhibitions.</i>

28:53.064 --> 28:54.482
<i>Seventeen years went by,</i>

28:57.193 --> 28:59.195
<i>and it was time to retire.</i>

28:59.279 --> 29:00.613
<i>It was in 1991.</i>

29:00.697 --> 29:03.366
<i>["L'amour L'amour L'amour"</i>
<i>by Marcel Moloudji playing]</i>

29:06.661 --> 29:09.831
<i>[in French] ♪ </i>Love, love, love… ♪

29:09.914 --> 29:12.250
<i>[Trinh] </i>But my passion pulled me…

29:12.792 --> 29:15.378
<i>♪ We always talk about… ♪</i>

29:15.462 --> 29:16.713
<i>…back to making shoes.</i>

29:19.841 --> 29:21.217
<i>I was already 60.</i>

29:21.301 --> 29:23.553
<i>♪ Is a timid spring ♪</i>

29:23.636 --> 29:24.596
<i>[machine whirring]</i>

29:24.679 --> 29:27.015
<i>♪ </i>A tender light ♪

29:27.599 --> 29:30.310
<i>♪ Or often a downfall ♪</i>

29:31.853 --> 29:33.980
<i>♪ Love… ♪</i>

29:35.482 --> 29:38.109
<i>[Pope Francis] </i>On the one hand,
there's automatic work,

29:38.193 --> 29:40.653
<i>and then there's the work</i>
<i>you put your soul into.</i>

29:42.238 --> 29:44.616
<i>And the idea of the work</i>
<i>you put your soul into,</i>

29:45.158 --> 29:47.243
<i>where you leave your mark,</i>

29:47.327 --> 29:49.287
<i>is the idea of the craftsman.</i>

29:49.370 --> 29:52.999
<i>Even if it's not handmade,</i>
<i>you still put your heart into it, right?</i>

29:53.500 --> 29:55.251
<i>You don't go on autopilot, do you?</i>

29:55.960 --> 29:58.254
<i>When work is automatic, it's dangerous.</i>

30:00.131 --> 30:04.969
<i>That's why</i>
<i>a good worker is always creative.</i>

30:06.679 --> 30:09.557
<i>They're not automatic.</i>
<i>They bring a gift to others.</i>

30:14.229 --> 30:16.147
<i>[inspirational music playing]</i>

30:17.273 --> 30:18.650
<i>Try walking back and forth.</i>

30:20.610 --> 30:23.822
<i>-Ah, it's perfect! They fit?</i>
<i>-Yes. Thank you so much.</i>

30:23.905 --> 30:25.698
<i>Thank you. I really hope to see you again.</i>

30:25.782 --> 30:26.991
<i>-Of course.</i>
<i>-[Trinh] Yes.</i>

30:28.868 --> 30:29.869
<i>[customer] Goodbye.</i>

30:30.453 --> 30:31.996
<i>[inspirational music soars]</i>

30:34.249 --> 30:36.251
<i>[Trinh] </i>If you're passionate
about your work<i>,</i>

30:37.710 --> 30:39.671
<i>you can work all your life.</i>

30:44.425 --> 30:46.719
<i>I'll work until my last minute.</i>

30:46.803 --> 30:47.804
<i>[music continues]</i>

31:01.526 --> 31:02.360
<i>[music stops]</i>

31:02.443 --> 31:03.987
<i>[man yelling indistinctly]</i>

31:08.908 --> 31:09.742
<i>How are you?</i>

31:10.243 --> 31:14.622
<i>My family arrived in Israel</i>
<i>in this refugee camp…</i>

31:17.876 --> 31:20.336
<i>with small aluminum shacks.</i>

31:21.379 --> 31:24.382
<i>Electricity wasn't even in our dreams.</i>

31:26.676 --> 31:29.387
<i>The toilet was for 5,000 people.</i>

31:30.680 --> 31:34.225
<i>A hole in the woods, stinking.</i>

31:38.146 --> 31:42.859
<i>My parents, one of the first things</i>
<i>they did when they arrived is</i>

31:43.484 --> 31:48.406
<i>putting seeds in the ground,</i>
<i>growing vegetables.</i>

31:49.198 --> 31:54.621
<i>Tomatoes and courgettes</i>
<i>and a special sort of winter squash.</i>

31:56.372 --> 31:58.166
<i>A small farm in the desert.</i>

32:01.544 --> 32:03.296
<i>It's written in the old books,</i>

32:04.297 --> 32:10.011
<i>"In the future, the non-fruit trees</i>
<i>of Israel, they will carry fruit."</i>

32:16.225 --> 32:19.103
<i>Cooking, it's not a talent. It's a memory.</i>

32:21.564 --> 32:26.194
<i>And then, for cooking,</i>
<i>you need one of the senses</i>

32:26.277 --> 32:29.489
<i>that we… we are not using today,</i>

32:30.907 --> 32:32.575
<i>smelling and sniffing.</i>

32:33.326 --> 32:34.202
<i>[sniffing]</i>

32:35.703 --> 32:38.206
<i>Blessed are Thou,</i>
<i>O Lord, King of the Universe,</i>

32:38.289 --> 32:40.667
<i>Thou who creates the variety of aromas.</i>

32:40.750 --> 32:42.418
<i>Amen. Amen.</i>

32:43.711 --> 32:46.005
<i>You smell if the food is rotten,</i>

32:47.382 --> 32:51.427
<i>if it's a poison,</i>
<i>and you can smell the danger.</i>

32:54.472 --> 32:57.433
<i>It's a matter of life or death.</i>

33:03.606 --> 33:05.316
<i>When I was 13,</i>

33:07.068 --> 33:09.612
<i>they took me to the Holocaust Cave.</i>

33:13.074 --> 33:15.410
<i>I was smelling the death.</i>

33:17.620 --> 33:18.454
<i>It was there.</i>

33:21.082 --> 33:22.250
<i>JEWS, GO TO YOUR LAND</i>

33:22.333 --> 33:23.376
<i>JEWS ENTER AT OWN RISK</i>

33:23.459 --> 33:25.294
<i>JEWS NOT WELCOME</i>
<i>UNWANTED GUESTS</i>

33:27.839 --> 33:34.387
<i>All my perspective of--</i>
<i>on life and the world</i>

33:34.887 --> 33:38.266
<i>came from this shock</i>
<i>of these things that I have seen.</i>

33:41.853 --> 33:47.358
<i>When we went out,</i>
<i>I am smelling the spring and freedom.</i>

33:55.074 --> 33:56.659
<i>[unsettling music playing]</i>

34:03.791 --> 34:04.625
<i>[Sara groans]</i>

34:06.002 --> 34:09.172
<i>[Natalia] </i>Sara is getting ready.
The baby is coming.

34:11.924 --> 34:13.384
<i>She's about to have her baby.</i>

34:16.929 --> 34:20.058
<i>The midwife will stay for a while,</i>
<i>until she's done with labor.</i>

34:21.142 --> 34:22.018
<i>[Sara grunts]</i>

34:23.644 --> 34:25.813
<i>She has to be strong. She has to be there.</i>

34:26.689 --> 34:29.025
<i>It's a huge commitment</i>
<i>midwives choose to make.</i>

34:30.693 --> 34:32.987
<i>-[Sara groans]</i>
<i>-[Natalia speaks indistinctly]</i>

34:39.327 --> 34:42.538
<i>Sometimes, some days,</i>
<i>I'm awake all night, till morning.</i>

34:47.043 --> 34:49.378
<i>I have to wait and see</i>
<i>if labor is progressing.</i>

34:49.921 --> 34:53.091
<i>9:00 p.m., 10:00 p.m.,</i>
<i>11:00 p.m., midnight,</i>

34:53.174 --> 34:55.510
<i>1:00 a.m., 2:00 a.m., till 3:00 a.m.</i>

35:01.849 --> 35:03.935
<i>I see she's in more pain than before.</i>

35:06.229 --> 35:07.855
<i>I can see she's already dilated.</i>

35:08.773 --> 35:09.941
<i>The baby's coming.</i>

35:10.858 --> 35:11.776
<i>It's going well.</i>

35:29.377 --> 35:31.337
<i>[Francesca] You told</i>
<i>a very interesting story</i>

35:31.420 --> 35:33.047
<i>about a man coming to look at your work</i>

35:33.131 --> 35:35.675
<i>when you were young</i>
<i>and rejecting it outright. [chuckles]</i>

35:35.758 --> 35:36.926
<i>What happened?</i>

35:37.426 --> 35:40.555
<i>[Martin] I think it was the late '60s.</i>
<i>I made my short films. Pretty successful.</i>

35:40.638 --> 35:42.181
<i>Shown at the New York Film Festival.</i>

35:42.265 --> 35:43.933
<i>They had received awards.</i>

35:44.016 --> 35:47.228
<i>So, I was always hustling to put together</i>
<i>some money to make a feature.</i>

35:47.311 --> 35:48.688
<i>That was the idea, make a feature.</i>

35:48.771 --> 35:51.065
<i>[Martin] We're gonna roll.</i>
<i>There should be some silence.</i>

35:51.149 --> 35:52.942
<i>-[man] Uh, Marty…</i>
<i>-Yes?</i>

35:53.651 --> 35:55.444
<i>-[man] Do you want us to roll now?</i>
<i>-Certainly.</i>

35:55.528 --> 35:56.863
<i>[man] Rolling. Quiet, please.</i>

35:56.946 --> 35:59.532
<i>[Martin] There was this, uh,</i>
<i>very wealthy gentleman,</i>

35:59.615 --> 36:02.451
<i>who was so devoted to the art of cinema,</i>

36:03.369 --> 36:05.830
<i>that he would occasionally write checks.</i>

36:07.081 --> 36:09.876
<i>My producer and I were waiting</i>
<i>outside the screening room.</i>

36:09.959 --> 36:14.213
<i>This gentleman who was in there,</i>
<i>older man, little, uh, uh…</i>

36:14.714 --> 36:20.052
<i>little glasses, sort of round glasses,</i>
<i>bowler hat, velvet collared coat, uh…</i>

36:21.012 --> 36:22.054
<i>beautiful suit…</i>

36:22.638 --> 36:25.558
<i>He came out of the screening room,</i>
<i>and he was smiling.</i>

36:25.641 --> 36:27.768
<i>And we figured, "Great. This is great!"</i>

36:27.852 --> 36:29.937
<i>And so my producer said,</i>
<i>"Well, what d'you think?"</i>

36:30.438 --> 36:32.023
<i>And the man said, "I didn't like it."</i>

36:35.193 --> 36:39.197
<i>And said, "If I saw one shred of talent</i>
<i>in there, I would tell you."</i>

36:40.489 --> 36:42.742
<i>We were stunned, shocked.</i>

36:43.534 --> 36:46.704
<i>And the only reaction we had was to laugh.</i>

36:46.787 --> 36:50.458
<i>The only thing we could do is--</i>
<i>That immediately made us say,</i>

36:50.541 --> 36:52.126
<i>"Okay, let's go on."</i>

36:54.253 --> 36:55.296
<i>"Let's continue."</i>

36:55.379 --> 36:57.381
<i>[man] Let's hold our horses a little,</i>
<i>okay?</i>

36:57.465 --> 37:00.509
<i>[man 2] Lights, guys, please.</i>
<i>Lights. Lights. Lights.</i>

37:00.593 --> 37:03.971
<i>[Martin] </i>No matter what, how many times
pictures have been rejected,

37:04.055 --> 37:05.514
<i>pictures have been criticized…</i>

37:06.974 --> 37:10.519
<i>Ultimately, the only thing that mattered</i>
<i>was if you needed to make another one,</i>

37:10.603 --> 37:12.021
<i>you had to make another one.</i>

37:12.104 --> 37:13.940
<i>That's who you are.</i>
<i>You're impelled to do it…</i>

37:15.942 --> 37:19.987
<i>and you get to do it,</i>
<i>it's… it's an extraordinary gift.</i>

37:20.071 --> 37:22.114
<i>That… That's the gift, doing it.</i>

37:22.198 --> 37:23.532
<i>[gentle music playing]</i>

37:34.919 --> 37:36.921
<i>[birds and insects chirping]</i>

37:43.678 --> 37:44.929
<i>[water dribbling]</i>

37:49.850 --> 37:52.895
<i>[Nike] </i>Osun River is a traditional grove.

37:54.230 --> 37:56.941
<i>That river is the one that keep our life.</i>

37:58.651 --> 38:00.778
<i>I have come today to thank you.</i>

38:02.113 --> 38:04.115
<i>You've granted all I asked for.</i>

38:05.908 --> 38:11.080
<i>[in Yoruba] Benevolent Mother.</i>
<i>Benevolent Mother of Osun!</i>

38:12.873 --> 38:16.836
<i>[in English] I came to Osun first in 1967.</i>

38:18.587 --> 38:20.464
<i>I came to ask a favor from Osun.</i>

38:20.965 --> 38:25.303
<i>I promised that if she could make me</i>
<i>a famous artist in Osogbo,</i>

38:26.345 --> 38:28.889
<i>I'd sing praises</i>
<i>of Osun all over the world.</i>

38:32.435 --> 38:36.814
<i>I also ask for a long life</i>
<i>and good health,</i>

38:38.357 --> 38:41.402
<i>to live out the rest of my life.</i>

38:43.404 --> 38:46.782
<i>Osun, I thank you, Goddess of Osun.</i>

38:52.121 --> 38:57.293
<i>Goddess of Osun!</i>
<i>Goddess of Osun! I've come to you.</i>

39:07.553 --> 39:09.722
<i>The secret is patience.</i>

39:10.806 --> 39:12.308
<i>They said if you have patience</i>

39:12.391 --> 39:15.519
<i>you will eat a meat</i>
<i>that is bigger than an elephant.</i>

